## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected â€” DSA still works there (though it's considered legacy everywhere).

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify existing legacy signatures**, you have two options:

### Option 1 â€” Platform-guard DSA (keep verifying on Windows/Linux only)

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification unavailable on macOS.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2 â€” Migrate to a modern algorithm (recommended long-term)

Re-sign your data with **ECDSA**, **RSA**, or **Ed25519**, then verify with the new key going forward:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

This requires a one-time re-signing step for all legacy artifacts.

### Practical recommendation

If you must keep verifying old DSA signatures unchanged, use **Option 1** and restrict DSA verification to Windows/Linux CI runners. For new signatures, adopt ECDSA across all platforms.
